r these kids. There is a lot of running around the room, a lot of chatting amongst the adults, a lot of playing games on the library's computer, a lot of fast food consumption. Meanwhile my own five kids who attend the local high quality public schools are working working working so hard to keep up with the demands and requirements of school. I often wonder if homeschool parents, whose children have never attended public schools, actually understand how intense and serious school is our county. I also think every parent is a homeschooling parent. I have been actively involved in teaching/supporting/encouraging my kids educational pursuits. Just because I send them to public school doesn't mean I wash my hands of the process. I am constantly seeking ways to supplement and support them at home. I know there are homeschooling families who do it right. But they are the exception, I fear. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1184" language="en" documentId="192" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="mgdj" date="7/29/2013 9:54 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/12606dc6-dd4f-449d-b12e-01792b2e628e/" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="192" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1184"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>